'''Kumenomiagata Shrine''' ({{ill|Kumenomiagata Shrine|ja|久米御縣神社|12=draft}}) is a [[Shinto shrine]] located in Kume Town, [[Kashihara City]], [[Nara Prefecture]]. It is a designated {{ill|Shikinai-sha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|12=draft}} and was Ranked as a [[Village Shrine]] under the [[Modern typeing System]].

== History ==
The exact origins of the shrine are unknown. Shrines named "Miagata Shrine" (御縣神社) exist in seven locations within the [[Yamato Province]], all of which were located on imperial estates called "Miagata" (御縣). According to the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft}}, Emperor Suinin's 27th year contains a record stating, "This year, a granary was established in Kume Village." It is believed that the shrine was established during this period.

The shrine is listed in the {{ill|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|ja|延喜式神名帳|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|12=draft}} as "Yamato Province, Takichi District, Kumenomiagata Shrine, Three Seats" and is categorized as a minor {{ill|Shikinai-sha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|12=draft}}. However, while the {{ill|Engishiki Kinen Norito|ja|延喜式祈年祝詞|12=draft}} mentions the other six Miagata Shrines, this shrine is excluded.

The decline of the [[Kume clan]] led to the deterioration of the shrine. It was later reconstructed as a guardian shrine for the adjacent {{ill|Kumedera Temple|ja|久米寺|12=draft}} and became known as Tenjinja or Kumemiya. By the mid-[[Edo period]], it was commonly referred to as {{ill|Tenmangū|ja|天満宮|12=draft}} or Tenjinja, with numerous lanterns bearing these names still preserved.

In [[1868]] (first year of the [[Meiji era]]), during the separation of Shinto and Buddhism ({{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|ja|神仏分離|12=draft}}), the shrine was detached from Kumedera Temple and renamed Kumenomiagata Shrine in the mid-Meiji period. It was also designated as a [[Village Shrine]].

== Deities ==
* Primary Deities: {{ill|Takamimusubi no Mikoto|ja|高皇産霊命|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ōkumemikoto|ja|大来目命|12=draft}}, and Tenkushine no Mikoto

According to the ''Gokō-gun Shrine Records,'' the deity "Tenkushine no Ōkumemikoto" was initially treated as a single entity. The ''Shikinai-sha Chōsa Hōkoku'' suggests that the deity's name may have been divided into two during the early modern period.

Ōkumemikoto served [[Emperor Jimmu]] and is considered the ancestor of the [[Kume clan]]. The surrounding area, historically known as Kume Village, was home to the Kume clan, and the shrine enshrines their ancestral deity.

== Structures ==
* Main Hall - {{ill|Kasuga-zukuri|ja|春日造|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Kōdai Shrine|ja|皇大神社|12=draft}} - Deities: {{ill|Emperor Ōjin|ja|誉田別命|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ame-no-Koyane no Mikoto|ja|天児屋根命|1=Ame-no-Koyane|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|大日霊貴命|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Kumano Shrine|ja|熊野神社|12=draft}} - deity: {{ill|Izanami|ja|伊弉冉尊|12=draft}}
* Worship Hall
== See Also ==
* {{ill|Kume clan|ja|久米氏|12=draft}}

