'''Kume no Miagata Shrine''' ({{ill|Kume no Miagata Shrine|ja|久米御縣神社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kume no Miagata Shrine|qq=}}) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|en|Shinto shrine|qid=Q845945|lt=Shinto shrine|1=Shinto shrine}} located in Kume Town, [[Kashihara City]], {{ill|Nara Prefecture|en|Nara Prefecture|qid=Q131287|lt=Nara Prefecture|1=Nara Prefecture}}. It is a designated {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|2=ja|3=式内社|1=Shikinaisha|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikinaisha|13=User:Immanuelle|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|lt=Shikinaisha}} and was Ranked as a [[Village Shrine]] under the [[Modern system of ranked shinto shrines]].

== History ==
The exact origins of the shrine are unknown. Shrines named "Miagata Shrine" (御縣神社) exist in seven locations within the {{ill|Yamato Province|en|Yamato Province|qid=Q907495|lt=Yamato Province|1=Yamato Province}}, all of which were located on imperial estates called "Miagata" (御縣). According to the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|en|Nihon Shoki|qid=Q813935|lt=Nihon Shoki|1=Nihon Shoki}}, Emperor Suinin's 27th year contains a record stating, "This year, a granary was established in Kume Village." It is believed that the shrine was established during this period.

The shrine is listed in the {{ill|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki|ja|延喜式神名帳|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Engishiki Jinmyōchō|13=User:Immanuelle/Engishiki Jinmyōchō|qq=}} as "Yamato Province, Takichi District, Kume no Miagata Shrine, Three Seats" and is categorized as a minor {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|2=ja|3=式内社|1=Shikinaisha|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikinaisha|13=User:Immanuelle|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|lt=Shikinaisha}}. However, while the {{ill|Engishiki Kinen Norito|ja|延喜式祈年祝詞|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Engishiki Kinen Norito|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} mentions the other six Miagata Shrines, this shrine is excluded.

The decline of the [[Kume clan]] led to the deterioration of the shrine. It was later reconstructed as a guardian shrine for the adjacent {{ill|Kumedera Temple|ja|久米寺|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumedera Temple|1=Kume-dera Temple|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11369593}} and became known as Tenjinsha or Kumemiya. By the mid-{{ill|Edo period|en|Edo period|qid=Q184963|lt=Edo period|1=Edo period}}, it was commonly referred to as {{ill|Tenmangū|en|Tenmangū|qid=Q798838|lt=Tenmangū|1=Tenmangū}} or Tenjinsha, with numerous lanterns bearing these names still preserved.

In {{ill|1868|en|1868|qid=Q7717|lt=1868|1=1868}} (first year of the {{ill|Meiji era|en|Meiji era|qid=Q3125096|lt=Meiji era|1=Meiji era}}), during the separation of Shinto and Buddhism ({{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|en|Shinbutsu bunri|qid=Q1970535|lt=Shinbutsu bunri|1=Shinbutsu bunri}}), the shrine was detached from Kumedera Temple and renamed Kume no Miagata Shrine in the mid-Meiji period. It was also designated as a [[Village Shrine]].

